title: For Sale:  1529 rds. 8mm Mauser
postcontent: I have 1,529 rounds (laid out, counted, and pictured) of persian 8mm Mauser ammunition. This ammo is live and should be treated as such, however, because of its age (~1930s) it is best suited as components for reloading purposes. I no longer reload rifle rounds because I just don't have the time or motivation. I would pull the bullets, salvage the powder, de-prime the cases, and sell the brass to a scrap yard. This is a much cheaper way to reload for 8mm surplus rifles.Due to mass low baller spam I am setting the price to ~0.13 per round for a fixed price of $200 for all 1,529 rounds and cash only. The cheapest 8mm projectiles on the market currently are PPU at ~0.25 per bullet. At 0.13 per round you are getting a projectile, powder load, and brass to trade to a scrap yard for some money back or convert to boxer primers. You won't find 8mm components this cheap anywhere else, ever.If your email has anything other than "I'll take it" it's going straight to the trash folder, spammers will be blocked so don't waste your time. Just need to see an Arizona ID and you're good to go.

title: For Sale:  1903A3 smith carona PROJECT
postcontent: For sale is a 1903a3 30-06 smith carona PROJECT rifle. This one takes some explaining so hang in there, TLDR at the end.Bought this gun at a gun show from a guy a little over a year ago. Didn't really know what to look for with these guns and it gauged at 0 with a muzzle gauge so the price was right for me. Now the guy at the gun show told me this was a CMP/DCM rifle, sat in a closet for years and he wanted to sell it since he wasn't using it. I gave it the metaphorical shot. Later on when stripping the gun down for a cleaning I came to find out this is a restored drill rifle. I know this because there is evidence of a barrel spot weld under the reciever and the cuttoff seems to have been previously welded too. It headspaces fine, so I didnt think much of it and went and shot the rifle. I noticed after firing it that it makes rings around the brass. After talking with many people, I believe this to be a defect in the chamber, which you may need a chamber reamer to fix. I am worried that this may lead to case separations in the chamber, but it has never happened to me. I do not want to invest in a reamer or pay to have a restored drill rifle rebarreled. I dont know any good gunsmiths with the capability to fix this and don't want to spend the time and money to do it. I would rather just cut my losses and move on. That is why this is listed as a PROJECT rifle. It is fully functional right now, headspaces fine, and I have fired it a couple hundred times without issues, however the chamber issue described above bothers me. I have other 1903s, so my preference is to sell this rifle to someone who wants to fix it with a reamer or rebarrel it. Will this blow up if you don't fix the issue I have described? Probably not, but YOU are assuming the risk of injury if you buy this and do not fix the issue and just go shoot the rifle since this is listed on the cheap. That is why I am writing this in full disclosure. If none of this dissaudes you and you want to just buy the rifle and shoot it, so be it but now you know the issues. I didn't know these things when I bought this thing from a dishonest salesman at a gunshow, so it is only fair to lay them out in the open rather than screw another person over like he did me.All that said the stock on this rifle is very nice. I considered either parting out the rifle or making it a wall hanger but I would rather just do a quick sale and be done with it. Smith Carona reciever. Remington barrel with no wear at all. Unsure of the grove count. Parts all do not match.TLDR; Gun is a restored drill rifle with a chamber issue. Buy and shoot at your own risk. The price is low to encourage someone to buy and fix this, I do not want to bother with it.Price will be $400 OBO, face to face sale, Ohio DL
